<P>
<H2>
Background and Reseach Goals
</H2>

I received my B A in Computational Linguistics and Mathematics in 1988, a
Licentiate of Philosophy in Computer and Systems Sciences 1992, and have
since then been employed at SICS in the Language and Interaction group -
the former Natural Language Processing group. Currently I hold a part time
professorship at Helsinki University. I have previously worked at SISU,
been a visiting student at Columbia University, a programming assistant at
Xerox PARC, and an assistant research scientist in the <A
HREF="http://cs.nyu.edu/cs/projects/proteus/"> PROTEUS </A> project at New
York University. 

<p>

My primary interests are dialogue and communication, taken
broadly enough to include human computer dialogue design, information
retrieval, and language typology - my research has focused on ensuring that
multimodal human-computer dialogue provides enough cues for natural
language interaction to be natural, transparent, and intuitive; and in
investigating surface cues in texts to aid text categorization. My long
term research goal is to show how these two activities can be understood as
investigation of the same cognitive mechanisms.



<hr>
<H2>
Projects and Publications
</H2>
<P>



<H3>
<A NAME=Nontopic>
Text genres and text context or ecology:
</A>
</H3>

One of the research projects of the NLP group is to experiment
with non-topic information retrieval. The idea is to complement
standard information retrieval metrics which are based on a
shallow semantic analysis with a genre analysis and a usage
or text ecology analysis. An encouraging experiment on text genre recognition 
is described in a publication 
<A HREF="http://www.sics.se/~jussi/cmplglixcol.ps"> 
"Text genre recognition using discriminant analysis"
</A>
from 
<A HREF="http://xxx.lanl.gov/cmp-lg/Coling-94.html">
COLING 94, Kyoto, 1994
</A>,
and another experiment on text clustering based on usage statistics in a 
tech report 
<A HREF="http://www.sics.se/libabstracts.html#T94/04"> 
"Newsgroup clustering"
</A>
available at SICS. They are both brought together into a
common framework in an overview paper: 
<A HREF="http://www.sics.se/~jussi/distrnontopicir.ps"> 
"Non-topic information retrieval".
</A>
My work in New York relates to this theme. See the <a href="http://www.cs.nyu.edu/cs/projects/proteus/trec/">Proteus project
information retrieval page</a> for reports.
<H3>
<A NAME=Multimodal>
Multimodal discourse:
</A>
</H3>

The two projects DIVERSE and PUSH are multimodal interface experiments.
DIVERSE is a speech interface to a virtual reality environment, and PUSH is
a multimodal help system which allows users to pose queries by direct
manipulation in adaptive hypertext.


<ul>
<li>
<A HREF="http://www.sics.se/uacm/push.html">
PUSH home page. 
</A>

<li>
<A HREF="http://www.sics.se/nlp/diverse.html">
DIVERSE home page.
</A>
</ul>

